A Forward Proxy is a server that sits between clients and the internet, sending requests on behalf of the client.
Client → Forward Proxy → Internet (Servers)

What a Forward Proxy Does
1. Hides the Client
External servers see the proxy’s IP, not the client’s
Provides privacy and anonymity


2. Access Control
Blocks or allows websites
Enforces company or school policies

3. Caching
Stores frequently requested content
Speeds up access
Reduces bandwidth usage

4. Content Filtering & Security
Malware protection
Blocks unsafe or inappropriate sites
Inspects traffic (especially in enterprises)


Who Uses a Forward Proxy
Clients explicitly configure it
Common in:
Corporate networks
Schools
Privacy tools
